      • promptUserForFile

        public String promptUserForFile(String prompt)
        Asks the user to type a file name, re-prompting until the user types a file that exists in the current directory. The message "Unable to open that file. Try again." is shown every time a reprompt is necessary. The file's full path is returned as a string.
        Parameters:
        prompt - the text to display to the user
        directory - the working directory in which to look for files (e.g. "res/")
        Returns:
        the file name typed by the user, including any directory prefix, such as "res/input.txt" or "foo.dat"

      • promptUserForFile

        public String promptUserForFile(String prompt,
                                String directory)
        Asks the user to type a file name, re-prompting until the user types a file that exists in the given directory. The message "Unable to open that file. Try again." is shown every time a reprompt is necessary. The file's full path is returned as a string.
        Parameters:
        prompt - the text to display to the user
        directory - the working directory in which to look for files (e.g. "res/")
        Returns:
        the file name typed by the user, including any directory prefix, such as "res/input.txt" or "foo.dat"

      • promptUserForFile

        public String promptUserForFile(String prompt,
                                String directory,
                                String reprompt)
        Asks the user to type a file name, re-prompting until the user types a file that exists in the given directory. The given reprompt message is shown every time a reprompt is necessary. The file's full path is returned as a string.
        Parameters:
        prompt - the text to display to the user
        directory - the working directory in which to look for files (e.g. "res/")
        Returns:
        the file name typed by the user, including any directory prefix, such as "res/input.txt" or "foo.dat"

      • setFont

        public void setFont(String str)
        Sets the font used for the console as specified by the string str, which is interpreted in the style of Font.decode. The usual format of the font string is

        family-style-size

        where both style and size are optional. If any of these parts are specified as an asterisk, the existing value is retained.

        Parameters:
        str - A String specifying the new font
        Usage:
        program.setFont(str);
